The role of hormesis in life extension by dietary restriction.

Masoro EJ(1).

Author information:
(1)Barshop Institute for Longevity and Aging Studies, University of Texas Health 
Science Center, San Antonio, TX, USA. masoro@aol.com

The level of food restriction that results in life extension and retarded aging 
in rodents also enhances their ability to cope with intense stressors. Moreover, 
this level of dietary restriction (DR) leads to a modest increase in the daily 
peak concentration of plasma free corticosterone, which strongly points to DR as 
a low-intensity stressor. These findings suggest that hormesis plays a role in 
the life-extending and anti-aging actions of DR. The evidence for and against 
this possibility is considered, and it is concluded that hormesis does have an 
important role.

