oxidative stress and the plasma levels of asymmetric dimethylarginine (ADMA), an 
endogenous inhibitor of nitric oxide synthase. We confirmed that compared with 
age- and gender-matched healthy controls, ESRD patients have excessive oxidative 
stress and arginine methylation as indexed by elevated plasma levels of 
oxidation products of lipids (13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid (13-HODE)), thiols 
(oxidized:reduced glutathione, oxidized glutathione (GSSG):GSH), proteins, and 
nucleic acids, and the methylation products ADMA and symmetric dimethylarginine 
(SDMA). We undertook a double blind, crossover study of equi-antihypertensive 
treatment with amlodipine and valsartan for 6 weeks each to test our hypothesis. 
Both treatments significantly reduced GSSG:GSH, 8-hydroxy 2-deoxyguanosine, 
ADMA, and SDMA levels and amlodipine reduced 13-HODE. We conclude that 
hypertensive patients with ESRD receiving HD have evidence of extensive 
oxidation of lipids, thiols, proteins, and nucleic acids and methylation of 
arginine that could contribute to CVD. Many of these changes can be reduced by 
short-term treatment with amlodipine and valsartan.

